Throwing exceptions, and writing your own.

To raise an exception explicitly, you use the throw keyword. Whatever follows throw has to be a throwable, and in practice that is almost always an object you build right there with new. Most of the time you do not need a custom type at all, because the standard unchecked exceptions already cover the common cases. Illegal-argument exception is for when a caller passes a value outside what the method accepts. Illegal-state exception is for when a method is called while the object is not in a fit state to handle it. Null-pointer exception is for a required reference that turned out to be null, and there is a neat helper, objects dot require-non-null, that throws it with a clean message. And unsupported-operation exception is for an operation this particular implementation does not support.

So a parse-age method can throw an illegal-argument exception when the age comes out negative, with a message that says exactly what went wrong.

When the standard exceptions do not communicate enough, you write your own. The convention is to extend runtime exception for an unchecked type, or plain exception for a checked one, and to provide constructors that take a message, and optionally a cause. A nice touch is to carry structured data on the exception. An insufficient-funds exception, for instance, can hold the requested amount and the available amount as fields, so the code that catches it can react precisely, not just print a string.
